04212nam a22005175i 9780773590328DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735903287 a10.1515/97807735903282doi  a(DE-B1597)657005  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.E7bC65 2014eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.38/89712071932231 aCollings, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming Inummarik :bMen's Lives in an Inuit Community /cPeter Collings. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource :b3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v7300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMaps -- tTime for a Snack -- tThings are Really Changing Around Here -- tA Congenial Dolt Learns About Inuit Culture -- tHe’s a Good Friend, But He’s a Crook -- tDriving Around -- tI’m Experimenting -- tExpensive Women and Unbalanced Lives -- tSometimes I Can Feel Heavy -- tIt Feels Good to Give That Much -- tReal Northern Men -- tGlossary of Inuinnaqtun Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to become a man in the Arctic today? Becoming Inummarik focuses on the lives of the first generation of men born and raised primarily in permanent settlements. Forced to balance the difficulties of schooling, jobs, and money that are a part of village life with the conflicting demands of older generations and subsistence hunting, these men struggle to chart their life course and become inummariit - genuine people. Peter Collings presents an accessible, intelligent, humorous, and sensitive account of Inuit men who are no longer youths, but not yet elders. Based on over twenty years of research conducted in Ulukhaktok, Northwest Territories, Becoming Inummarik is a profound and nuanced look at contemporary Inuit life that shows not just what Inuit men do, but who they are. Collings recounts experiences from his immersion in the daily lives of Ulukhaktok's men - from hunting and sharing meals to playing cards and grocery shopping - to demonstrate how seemingly mundane activities provide revelations about complex issues such as social relationships, status, and maturity. He also reflects on the ethics of immersive anthropological research, the difficulties of balancing professional and personal relationships with informants, and the nature of knowledge in Inuit culture. Becoming Inummarik shows that while Inuit born into a modern society see themselves as different from their parents' generation, their adherence to traditional ideas about life ensures that they remain fully Inuit even as their community has witnessed drastic upheaval.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aInuitzNorthwest TerritorieszUlukhaktokxSocial conditions. 0aInuitzNorthwest TerritorieszUlukhaktokxSocial life and customs. 0aMasculinityxSocial aspectszNorthwest TerritorieszUlukhaktok. 0aMenzNorthwest TerritorieszUlukhaktokxSocial conditions. 0aMenzNorthwest TerritorieszUlukhaktokxSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359032840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773590328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773590328/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles